<h3 class="tool_heading">Memo from the District</h3>
<p>Thursday, April 16, 2020</p>
<p>Dear Families of the Augusta Area School District,</p>
<p>As you may have heard earlier today, Governor Evers extended the closure of schools for the remainder of the school year. In the bulleted items below, I have outlined how this will impact us moving throughout the remainder of April and through May.</p>
<p>Furthermore, Governor Evers directed the Department of Health Services to continue the Safer at Home order for the state of Wisconsin.  The Safer at Home order began on Wednesday, March 25 and will remain in effect until 8 a.m. on Tuesday, May 26, or until a superseding order is issued.</p>
<p>As a result of this order, Augusta Area High School, Augusta Area Middle School, Augusta Area Elementary School, and Wildlands School will remain closed and continue to deliver packet-based and/or digital instruction through the remainder of the school year.<br><br>
All of our school buildings will be closed to the public until further notice.</p>
<p>As a result, I have a few updates and pieces of information to share with you.</p>
<ul>
<li>Meals: Meal distribution will again take place on Friday. We will continue to use the same process for meal distribution as last week. If you have not received meals but would like to, please contact Jayne Yule at 715-286-3304.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Teacher contact: Teachers will continue to provide learning opportunities and instruction through Friday, May 29. The expectation from the district is that students continue to remain engaged in what teachers are providing and put forth the necessary effort. The week of June 1 will provide time for students to obtain their items from school and return any school materials they may have.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Student participation: Below is a link to a document we would like to share with you. The document contains recommendations for minimum and maximum guidelines related to time students should be spending with their learning on a weekly basis. This is being shared with you to help answer questions and hopefully alleviate stress that many parents are currently feeling related to this. The most significant thing I can stress is the continued encouragement of your children to engage with their teachers throughout the remaining weeks ahead. This will allow students to remain mentally stimulated and will assist in the transition back to a “normal” school routine when we are again able to open our doors.</li>
</ul>
<p><a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1r94iCLv9Zj_hhSOheHuGpVqlBn2jPfw7HMqe22JX7vM/edit?usp=sharing">https://docs.google.com/document/d/1r94iCLv9Zj_hhSOheHuGpVqlBn2jPfw7HMqe22JX7vM/edit?usp=sharing</a></p>
<ul>
<li>Grading: A question that has arisen on multiple occasions is the measuring of student learning and work at the high school level. As Mr. Pecha has previously shared with you the grades for 2<sup>nd</sup> semester will be determined on a pass/fail basis. Teachers will be measuring this largely by the time and effort students are putting forth related to the material being provided. If you have specific questions about what your son or daughter may be doing for his/her teacher, I would encourage you to contact them directly. Mrs. Steinmetz and Mr. Pecha will be sending additional correspondence with further details on Friday, April 17.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Summer school: We are making plans to conduct summer school in the months of June, July, and August. We are also planning to add additional weeks of summer school instruction this summer. Last year we offered 4 weeks of summer school instruction. Our current plans include offering a minimum of 6 weeks of summer school. Our summer school coordinator, Mrs. Teri Hoff, will be sending further details in the near future about summer school. In the event the State of Wisconsin does not allow us to hold onsite summer school courses we will be developing online and virtual course options.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Spring sports: Due to the extended closure, unfortunately the spring sports season will be cancelled.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Graduation: With today’s announcement, our senior graduation ceremony will not be able to be held in the traditional manner on May 22 as was originally planned. Instead, plans are being developed to conduct a normal graduation commencement ceremony at a later date. All seniors will be sent a survey to obtain their feedback on what ceremony options are most favored.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Prom: Our prom advisors, Ms. Bergum and Ms. Patterson, are currently working with the junior class on developing plans to host prom at a later time. Once details are finalized they will be shared.</li>
</ul>
<p>If you have any questions, concerns, or just need clarification please don’t hesitate to contact our staff, our administration, or myself. We will do our best to help.</p>
<p>Take care and be safe,</p>
<p>Ryan C. Nelson</p>
<p>District Administrator</p>
